07156nam a22010575i 9783110552386DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105523867 a10.1515/97831105523862doi  a(DE-B1597)482825  a(OCoLC)1121054959  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aBP163b.P45 2019 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a181.0722300aPhilosophy in the Islamic World in Context. nVolume 1, pPhilosophy and Jurisprudence in the Islamic World /ced. by Peter Adamson. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (XII, 316 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPhilosophy in the Islamic World in Context ;vVolume 100tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tPreface -- tPhilosophical Reflections in the Poetry of al-Shāfiʿī -- tEthics and Fiqh in al-Fārābī’s Philosophy -- tIbn Sīnā’s Moral Ontology and Theory of Law -- tIn the Footsteps of Ibn Sīnā? The Uṣūlī Debate on the Argumentum e Contrario -- tAl-Ghazālī on Philosophy and Jurisprudence -- tSyllogistic Logic in Islamic Legal Theory: al-Ghazālī’s Arguments for the Certainty of Legal Analogy (Qiyās) -- tDeontic Modalities in Ibn Ḥazm -- tSplitting the Process and the Result: Philosophy from a Legal Perspective in Averroes’ Decisive Treatise -- tFoundations of Ibn Taymiyya’s Religious Utilitarianism -- tValue Ontology and the Assumption of Non-Assessment in Postclassical Shīʿī Legal Theory -- tTajarrī as Religious Luck -- tConcomitance to Causation: Arguing Dawarān in the Proto-Ādāb al-Baḥth -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book brings together the study of two great disciplines of the Islamic world: law and philosophy. In both sunni and shiite Islam, it became the norm for scholars to acquire a high level of expertise in the legal tradition. Thus some of the greatest names in the history of Aristotelianism were trained jurists, like Averroes, or commented on the status and nature of law, like al-Fārābī. While such authors sought to put law in its place relative to the philosophical disciplines, others criticized philosophy from a legal viewpoint, like al-Ghazālī and Ibn Taymiyya. But this collection of papers does not only explore the relative standing of law and philosophy. It also looks at how philosophers, theologians, and jurists answered philosophical questions that arise from jurisprudence itself. What is the logical structure of a well-formed legal argument? What standard of certainty needs to be attained in passing down judgments, and how is that standard reached? What are the sources of valid legal judgment and what makes these sources authoritative? May a believer be excused on grounds of ignorance? Together the contributions provide an unprecedented demonstration of the close connections between philosophy and law in Islamic society, while also highlighting the philosophical interest of texts normally studied only by legal historians.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aIslam and philosophy. 0aIslamic law. 0aIslamic. 4aFiqh. 4aIslam. 4aPhilosophie. 4aRechtslehre. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aIslam.  aPhilosophy.  afiqh.  ajurisprudence.1 aAdamson, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAkl, Ziad Bou, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBouhafa, Feriel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErlwein, Hannah C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGleave, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoover, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary